name: TikTok ban
summary: The Senate recently passed a bill that could potentially ban or restrict TikTok in the United States. The bill requires TikTok's parent company, ByteDance, to divest its interest in the app or face a ban. However, the bill still needs to be passed by the House of Representatives before it can be sent to President Biden for his signature. If signed into law, the ban would not take effect until after the 2024 presidential election. The legislation has raised concerns about the potential impact on free speech and innovation, as well as the ability of the government to effectively regulate social media companies. Despite these concerns, the bill appears to have bipartisan support and is expected to pass both chambers of Congress. Once signed into law, the government would have to determine how to enforce the ban and address any legal challenges that may arise.

name: FTC non-compete
summary: The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) has issued a final rule prohibiting employers from using non-compete clauses in most employment agreements. The new rule, which will go into effect in six months, bans non-compete clauses that prevent workers from seeking employment with other companies or starting their own businesses. The FTC received over 26,000 public comments on the proposed rule, with many businesses and industry groups opposing the ban. However, the FTC determined that non-compete clauses harm workers by limiting their ability to earn a living and stifle innovation and competition. The ban is expected to face legal challenges, with the U.S. Chamber of Commerce vowing to sue. The FTC's ban represents a significant shift in the legal landscape regarding non-compete agreements, which have been widely used by employers to protect their trade secrets and confidential information.

name: BostonBruins
summary: The Boston Bruins have made several roster moves, recalling John Beecher and Mason Lohrei to bolster their lineup. In their first-round playoff series opener against the Toronto Maple Leafs, Jake DeBrusk scored two power-play goals, and Jeremy Swayman made 35 saves to secure a 5-1 victory. The series schedule has been released, with Game 2 set for Toronto. The Bruins have also assigned Jayson Megna to their AHL affiliate in Providence. Meanwhile, Connor Clifton is listed as "week-to-week" with an injury, and will not travel to Toronto for Game 2. The team's medical director has provided updates on the care provided to athletes. Three Bruins stars, Brad Marchand, David Pastrnak, and Patrice Bergeron, are identified as key to the team's Stanley Cup aspirations. Despite their Game 1 victory, the Bruins suffered a loss in Game 2, prompting post-game reactions from players and coaches.
